title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R=\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be an Abelian group. Then there exists <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> positive integers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n_{1}]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n_{s}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in \mathbb {N}_{0}]]></fr:tex> such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[G\cong \mathbb {Z}^{r}\times  Z_{n_{1}}\times …\times  Z_{n_{s}}]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z_{n_{j}}=\mathbb {Z} / n_{j}\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> is a cyclic group of order <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n_{j}]]></fr:tex>. Moreover this decomposition is unique up to reordering the factors of finite Abelian groups.</fr:p>
 
   
